{{Sociology}}
'''Group threat theory''', also known as '''group position theory''',<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Thompson |first=Derek |date=2016-05-13 |title=Donald Trump and the Twilight of White America |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/05/donald-trump-and-the-twilight-of-white-america/482655/ |magazine=The Atlantic |language=en-US}}</ref> is a sociological theory which proposes that the larger the size of an [[Ingroups and outgroups|outgroup]], the more the corresponding [[ingroup]] perceives it to threaten its own interests, resulting in the ingroup members having more negative attitudes toward the outgroup.<ref name=schlueter>{{cite journal|last1=Schlueter|first1=Elmar|last2=Scheepers|first2=Peer|title=The relationship between outgroup size and anti-outgroup attitudes: A theoretical synthesis and empirical test of group threat- and intergroup contact theory|journal=Social Science Research|date=March 2010|volume=39|issue=2|pages=285–295|doi=10.1016/j.ssresearch.2009.07.006}}</ref> It is based on the work of [[Herbert Blumer]] and [[Hubert M. Blalock, Jr.]] in the 1950s and 1960s, and has since been supported by multiple studies.<ref name=schlueter/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kanas|first1=Agnieszka|last2=Scheepers|first2=Peer|last3=Sterkens|first3=Carl|title=Interreligious Contact, Perceived Group Threat, and Perceived Discrimination|journal=Social Psychology Quarterly|date=June 2015|volume=78|issue=2|pages=102–126|doi=10.1177/0190272514564790}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eitle|first1=D|last2=Taylor|first2=J|title=Are Hispanics the new 'threat'? Minority group threat and fear of crime in Miami-Dade County.|journal=Social Science Research|date=December 2008|volume=37|issue=4|pages=1102–15|pmid=19227693|pmc=4221266}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dixon|first1=Jeffrey C.|last2=Rosenbaum|first2=Michael S.|title=Nice to Know You? Testing Contact, Cultural, and Group Threat Theories of Anti-Black and Anti-Hispanic Stereotypes*|journal=Social Science Quarterly|date=June 2004|volume=85|issue=2|pages=257–280|doi=10.1111/j.0038-4941.2004.08502003.x}}</ref> Other studies, however, have not found support for the theory.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hjerm|first1=Mikael|title=Do Numbers Really Count? Group Threat Theory Revisited|journal=Journal of Ethnic and Migration Studies|date=October 2007|volume=33|issue=8|pages=1253–1275|doi=10.1080/13691830701614056}}</ref> Its predictions are contrary to those of the [[contact hypothesis]], which posits that greater proximity between racial/ethnic groups increases harmony between them.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dixon|first1=J. C.|title=The Ties That Bind and Those That Don't: Toward Reconciling Group Threat and Contact Theories of Prejudice|journal=Social Forces|date=1 June 2006|volume=84|issue=4|pages=2179–2204|doi=10.1353/sof.2006.0085}}</ref>
