{{Refimprove|date=September 2018}}
{{About|the anthems of nation states|anthems of other territories|List of anthems of non-sovereign countries, regions and territories}}
[[File:Marseillaisenoframe.jpg|300px|thumb|[[Claude Joseph Rouget de Lisle|Rouget de Lisle]], the composer of the French national anthem "[[La Marseillaise]]", sings it for the first time. The anthem is one of the earliest to be adopted by a modern state, in 1795.]]
Most [[nation-states]] have [[anthem]]s, defined as "a song, as of praise, devotion, or patriotism";<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-06-26|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/anthem|title=Anthem |publisher=Lexico Publishing Group|work=[[Reference.com]] }}</ref> most anthems are either [[March (music)|marches]] or [[hymn]]s in style. A hymn can become a [[national anthem]] by a provision in the state's constitution, by a law enacted by its legislature, or simply by tradition.<ref name="brit">{{cite encyclopedia|title=National anthem|encyclopedia=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]|year=2008}}</ref> A [[royal anthem]] is a patriotic song similar to a national anthem, but it specifically praises or prays for a monarch or royal [[dynasty]]. Such anthems are usually performed at public appearances by the monarch or during other events of royal importance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/progs/cpsc-ccsp/sc-cs/godsave_e.cfm |title=Royal anthem "God Save The Queen" |publisher=[[Department of Canadian Heritage]] |date= |accessdate=2008-04-17 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808013133/http://www.pch.gc.ca/progs/cpsc-ccsp/sc-cs/godsave_e.cfm |archivedate=2008-08-08 }}</ref> Some states use the royal anthem as the national anthem, such as the [[The Royal Anthem of Jordan|anthem of Jordan]].

There are multiple claimants to the position of oldest national anthem.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://nationalanthems.me/more/worlds-oldest-national-anthems/ | title=What are the world’s oldest national anthems? | publisher=NationalAnthems.me | accessdate=2011-08-14 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222060041/http://nationalanthems.me/more/worlds-oldest-national-anthems/ | archive-date=2011-12-22 | dead-url=yes | df= }}</ref> Among the national anthems, the first to be [[Musical composition|composed]] was the Dutch national anthem the "[[Wilhelmus]]", which was written between 1568 and 1572.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17 |url=http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/english/content.jsp?objectid=13327 |title=The Dutch Royal House |publisher=[[Dutch Royal House]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080210032558/http://www.koninklijkhuis.nl/english/content.jsp?objectid=13327 |archivedate=2008-02-10 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> The Japanese anthem, "[[Kimigayo]]", employs the oldest lyrics of any national anthem, taking its words from the "[[Kokin Wakashū]]", which was first published in 905, yet these words were not set to music until 1880.<ref name="jpri">Japan Policy Research Institute [http://www.jpri.org/publications/workingpapers/wp79.html JPRI Working Paper No. 79]. Published July 2001. Retrieved July 7, 2007</ref> The first anthem to be officially adopted as such was the Spanish anthem "[[La Marcha Real|Marcha Real]]", in 1770; its origins remain unclear, being suggested to have sixteenth century [[Venice|Venetian]] origins, or even to have been composed by king [[Frederick the Great]] himself; it is also one of the few national anthems that has never had official lyrics.<ref name="economist.com">{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17|url=http://www.economist.com/world/europe/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9558331|title=Lost for words|publisher=''[[The Economist]]''|date=2007-07-26}}</ref><!-- A national competition to write words for the anthem was launched in 2007;<ref name="economist.com" /> however, widespread public criticism forced the new lyrics to be withdrawn in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-05-01|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/01/16/europe/EU-GEN-Spain-Anthem-Controversy-Domingo.php|title=Controversy over lyrics stalls Placido Domingo's dream of singing Spanish anthem |publisher="[[International Herald Tribune]]"|date=2008-01-16 }}</ref>--> Anthems became increasingly popular among European states in the 18th century.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-10-02|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=93283699|title='Bird's Nest' Ballads: Olympic National Anthems |publisher=NPR|date=2008-08-07 }}</ref> For example, the British national anthem "[[God Save the Queen]]" was first performed under the title "God Save the King" in 1745.<ref>{{cite journal|title=God Save the King|publisher=''[[The Gentleman's Magazine]]''|date=October 1745|page=552|volume=15}}</ref> The French anthem "[[La Marseillaise]]" was written half a century later in 1792, and adopted in 1795.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17|url=http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/mod/marseill.html|title=La Marseillaise|publisher=[[Fordham University]]}}</ref>

National anthems are usually written in the most common language of the state, whether ''[[De facto#National languages|de facto]]'' or [[Official language|official]]. States with multiple national languages may offer several versions of their anthem. For instance, Switzerland's national anthem has different lyrics for each of the country's four official languages: French, German, Italian, and [[Romansh language|Romansh]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17|url=http://www.ch.ch/schweiz/01063/01065/index.html?lang=en|title=Facts and figures|publisher=[[Government of Switzerland]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080611082541/http://www.ch.ch/schweiz/01063/01065/index.html?lang=en|archivedate=2008-06-11|df=}}</ref> One of New Zealand's [[National anthems of New Zealand|two national anthems]] is commonly sung with the first verse in [[Māori language|Māori]] ("Aotearoa") and the second in [[English language|English]] ("God Defend New Zealand"). The tune is the same but the lyrics have different meanings. [[National anthem of South Africa|South Africa's national anthem]] is unique in that it is two different songs put together with five of the country's eleven official languages being used, in which each language comprises a [[stanza]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2008-04-17|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/jan/17/kosovo.serbia|title=There are great national anthems – now we need an international one |publisher="[[The Guardian]]"|date=2008-01-17|author=Ash, Timothy Garton }}</ref>

